# Git Workflow (MANDATORY)

## Branch Strategy

**NEVER commit directly to `main`.** All work happens on `develop`.

```
develop  ←── all ticket work (test locally)
   │
   └──▶ main  ←── merge develop when verified (stable)
```

No feature branches. No PRs. Solo developer workflow.

Before writing ANY code:

1. Ensure you are on `develop`:
   ```
   git switch develop
   ```
2. Do ALL work on `develop`. Commit directly here.

## Commit Conventions

- Use Conventional Commits: `feat:`, `test:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`
- Reference the ticket ID in every commit message:
  ```
  feat: implement chain-of-thought evaluator (P1-04)
  test: add golden set regression tests (P0-07)
  docs: update decision log with weighting rationale (P1-05)
  ```
- Commit in logical increments:
  1. Tests first (TDD)
  2. Implementation
  3. Documentation / decision log updates

## Merging to Main

When work is verified on `develop`:

```bash
git switch main && git merge develop && git push origin main
git switch develop
```

## Phase Boundaries

- When completing the last ticket in a phase, note it in the commit:
  ```
  feat: complete P0 foundation phase — all calibration tickets done (P0-08)
  ```
- Do NOT start a new phase's work before the prior phase is merged to main

## What NOT to Do

- Do NOT commit to `main` directly — merge via `develop`
- Do NOT create feature branches — work directly on `develop`
- Do NOT rebase or force-push without explicit user approval
- Do NOT commit `.env`, API keys, or `__pycache__/`
